<item>
            <title>[GROOVY-8321] !instanceof treated incorrectly in type checker</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/GROOVY-8321</link>
                <project id="12318123" key="GROOVY">Groovy</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;Currently in:&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/apache/groovy/blob/183b8fbf0248a2dceffbba684e50c3c2c060e46c/src/main/org/codehaus/groovy/transform/stc/StaticTypeCheckingVisitor.java#L703&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://github.com/apache/groovy/blob/183b8fbf0248a2dceffbba684e50c3c2c060e46c/src/main/org/codehaus/groovy/transform/stc/StaticTypeCheckingVisitor.java#L703&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The `instanceof` and `!instanceof` operators are treated the same when in fact the exact opposite is required.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Consider the following code where the `instanceof` has been &lt;em&gt;accidentally&lt;/em&gt; replaced with `!instanceof`. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-java&quot;&gt;[42, &lt;span class=&quot;code-quote&quot;&gt;&apos;bar&apos;&lt;/span&gt;].each { doit(it) }

@groovy.transform.TypeChecked
doit(arg) {
  &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;if&lt;/span&gt; (arg !&lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;instanceof&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;code-object&quot;&gt;String&lt;/span&gt;) {
    println arg.toUpperCase() &lt;span class=&quot;code-comment&quot;&gt;// MME: &lt;span class=&quot;code-object&quot;&gt;Integer&lt;/span&gt;.toUpperCase()
&lt;/span&gt;  } &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;else&lt;/span&gt; {
    &lt;span class=&quot;code-comment&quot;&gt;// println arg.toUpperCase() // [STC] [Static type checking] - Cannot find &lt;span class=&quot;code-object&quot;&gt;Object&lt;/span&gt;#toUpperCase()
&lt;/span&gt;    println &lt;span class=&quot;code-quote&quot;&gt;&apos;is a number&apos;&lt;/span&gt;
  }
}
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We&apos;d now expect the `toUpperCase` call to fail compilation but it succeeds and then fails at runtime.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Bonus points if the commented line in the else clause can be made to work.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
